      "content": "• The Global Markets saw a significant shift on Tuesday.\n• Central banks signaled a prolonged period of high interest rates to combat stubborn inflation.\n• The Federal Reserve indicated that while inflation is cooling, it remains above the 2% target threshold.\n• This led to a 1.2% drop in the S&P 500.\n• The S&P 500 drop was largely due to the Federal Reserve's decision to maintain high interest rates.\n• The Federal Reserve's decision was made in response to stubborn inflation.\n• Stubborn inflation is defined as inflation that exceeds the 2% target threshold.\n• The 2% target threshold is set by the Federal Reserve.\n• The Federal Reserve is responsible for setting monetary policy in the United States.\n• The Federal Reserve's monetary policy decisions have a significant impact on the US economy.\n• The US economy is a major player in the global economy.\n• The global economy is affected by a variety of factors, including interest rates and inflation.\n• Central banks around the world are closely monitoring interest rates and inflation.\n• Central banks use interest rates to control inflation and stimulate economic growth.\n• The goal of central banks is to maintain low and stable inflation.\n• Low and stable inflation is essential for economic growth.\n•",
